The finite difference time domain (FDTD) method has exploded
in popularity in recent years as illustrated by the steady
increase in conference presentations and journal articles. FDTD
is a popular method because it is simple, efficient, robust, and
highly accurate, and it easily treats general time domain excitations
and objects with complicated shape and/or material composition.




Several authors have recently applied the FDTD method to antenna radiation problems. Reineh and Jecko [ I ] analyzed radiation from a microstrip patch antenna using a general timedependent wave form. Their results were presented as a spatial distribution of current on the radiating element, input impedance versus frequency, and normalized radiation pattems. Maloney and Smith [2] analyzed radiation from circularly symmetric wire and conical monopole antennas in two dimensions using a
general time-dependent wave form. Their results were in the form of time domain far-zone radiation and input admittance versus frequency. Tirkas and Balanis [3] and Katz et aE. [41
analyzed radiation from rectangular waveguides and pyramidal
horn antennas in two and three dimensions using sinusoidal
excitation and the contour path FDTD method [5]. Results from
these analyses were also presented as normalized radiation
patterns. Luebbers and Beggs [61 have shown wideband absolute
gain and efficiency computations for dipole antennas. To the
authors' knowledge, no previously published work exists regarding
the application of the FDTD method to radiation from
circular waveguides and/or circular antenna structures. More
importantly, absolute gain computations have not been shown in
FDTD analyses of shaped-end radiators.

This communication presents the application of the FDTD
method to the analysis of electromagnetic radiation from circular
waveguides and other "shaped-end radiators" (SERs or
Vlasov radiator). A straight-cut circular waveguide and two
separate SERs are analyzed using a sinusoidal wave form.
Absolute gain versus angle is presented for all three cases and
data are compared against measured data.
